"{\"correct\": \"no\", \"explanation\": \"The OneHotEncoder in scikit-learn does not directly support string input. It requires integer input. However, in this code snippet, column 'b' is of type object which contains strings. To fix this issue, we need to use the OneHotEncoder with the parameter 'handle_unknown' set to 'ignore' if we are certain that there will be no new categories in the test data. However, a more robust solution would be to use pandas.get_dummies() to one-hot encode the categorical variables before passing them to the pipeline. Alternatively, we can use LabelEncoder to convert the categorical variables into integers before passing them to the OneHotEncoder.\", \"patch\": \"19,22c19,22\\n< preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([\\n<     ('numeric', MinMaxScaler(), ['a']),\\n<     ('categoric', OneHotEncoder(), [\\\"b\\\"])\\n< ])\\n---\\n> from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\\n> le = LabelEncoder()\\n> X_train['b'] = le.fit_transform(X_train['b'])\\n> X_test['b'] = le.transform(X_test['b'])\\n> preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([\\n>     ('numeric', MinMaxScaler(), ['a']),\\n>     ('categoric', OneHotEncoder(), [\\\"b\\\"])\\n> ])\\n\"}"